## RLS policy blueprint

General rules:
- Enable RLS on all tables
- Policies check auth.uid() for membership
- Provide explicit owner-only write policies for project_members
- Avoid recursive policies (no chain of policies relying on each other)

Examples (pseudo-SQL):

Enable RLS
- alter table projects enable row level security;
- alter table project_members enable row level security;
- alter table entries enable row level security;
- alter table evidence_files enable row level security;

projects (read for members, full control for owner)
- SELECT: exists(select 1 from project_members pm where pm.project_id = projects.id and pm.user_id = auth.uid())
- INSERT: with SECURITY DEFINER RPC create_project()
- UPDATE/DELETE: owner-only (projects.owner_id = auth.uid())

project_members
- SELECT: member-only for that project
- INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE: owner-only of the project

entries
- SELECT: members
- INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE: editor/owner (or owner shortcut)
- Owner-bypass policy: projects.owner_id = auth.uid()

evidence_files
- SELECT: members (project scope)
- INSERT/DELETE: editor/owner
- Owner-bypass policy

SECURITY DEFINER RPCs
- create_project(p_owner_id uuid, p_name text, p_desc text) returns uuid
  - Inserts project row (owner_id = p_owner_id)
  - Inserts project_members(owner role) for owner
  - Returns id
- add_member(p_project uuid, p_user uuid, p_role text) owner‑only check inside function

Storage (Supabase)
- Bucket: evidence
- File path convention: evidence/{project_id}/{hash}.{ext}
- Storage policies:
  - SELECT: project member
  - INSERT: editor or owner
  - DELETE: owner or editor
- Implement using jwt's user id and a SQL function to validate membership by parsing file path’s project_id

